    <div class="faq-section">
      <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

      <div class="faq-item">
        <div class="faq-q">Can men over 50 still build muscle?</div>
        <div class="faq-a">Yes. The research is clear that men over 50 can build and preserve muscle with the right inputs — adequate protein (1.2g/kg or more daily), consistent resistance training 2–3 days per week, and sufficient sleep. The process is slower than at 30, but it works. The bigger obstacle is usually not biology — it's not having the right information.</div>
      </div>

      <div class="faq-item">
        <div class="faq-q">How much protein do you need to build muscle after 50?</div>
        <div class="faq-a">Men over 50 should target at least 1.2g of protein per kilogram of bodyweight daily — significantly more than the outdated RDA of 0.8g/kg. For a 185-pound man, that's roughly 100g per day, distributed across 3–4 meals at 30g or more per sitting. Most men over 50 are hitting closer to 60–70g without realizing it.</div>
      </div>

      <div class="faq-item">
        <div class="faq-q">How often should men over 50 lift weights?</div>
        <div class="faq-a">2–3 days per week of resistance training is sufficient and sustainable for most men over 50. The key is consistency and progressive overload — gradually increasing the challenge over time. More is not always better; recovery becomes more important after 50, and rest days are part of the plan, not a gap in it.</div>
      </div>

      <div class="faq-item">
        <div class="faq-q">Why does sleep matter for building muscle after 50?</div>
        <div class="faq-a">Sleep is when the majority of muscle protein synthesis and repair occurs. Growth hormone — which drives muscle recovery — is released primarily during deep sleep. Men over 50 who consistently sleep fewer than 7 hours are limiting their results regardless of how well they train or eat. Sleep isn't passive recovery; it's an active part of the muscle-building process.</div>
      </div>

      <div class="faq-item">
        <div class="faq-q">What is the biggest mistake men over 50 make when trying to build muscle?</div>
        <div class="faq-a">The most common mistake is inconsistency driven by overcomplicated plans. Men over 50 who try to track every calorie, follow complex periodization programs, and optimize every variable tend to quit within weeks. The plan that works is the one you actually follow for months — not the theoretically optimal one you abandon after two weeks.</div>
